`Approach 2: Dynamic Programming with Divisor CachingAn alternative approach leverages the key observation that if aja_jaj​ divides aia_iai​, then aja_jaj​ must be a divisor of aia_iai​. Instead of comparing aia_iai​ with every previous element, we compute all the divisors of aia_iai​ and check if any of those divisors have been seen before.

We maintain a dictionary (or map) called `best` where `best[x]` represents the maximum length of a fully dividing subsequence ending with value xxx. For each element xxx, we do the following:


Compute the list of divisors of xxx.
Find the maximum chain length among all divisors ddd of xxx that have appeared before by checking `best[d]`.
Set dp=(max&nbsp;chain&nbsp;length)+1dp = (\text{max chain length}) + 1dp=(max&nbsp;chain&nbsp;length)+1 and update `best[x]` accordingly.
To optimize the divisor computation, we use caching so that we do not recalculate divisors for the same number multiple times. This approach reduces the number of comparisons, especially when numbers have few divisors.

Below are the implementations in C++ and Python.

`#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;vector&gt;
#include &lt;unordered_map&gt;
#include &lt;cmath&gt;
#include &lt;algorithm&gt;
using namespace std;

vector&lt;long long&gt; getDivisors(long long x) {
    vector&lt;long long&gt; divs;
    for (long long i = 1; i * i &lt;= x; i++) {
        if (x % i == 0) {
            divs.push_back(i);
            if (i != x / i)
                divs.push_back(x / i);
        }
    }
    return divs;
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n;
    cin &gt;&gt; n;
    vector&lt;long long&gt; arr(n);
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++){
        cin &gt;&gt; arr[i];
    }
    unordered_map&lt;long long, int&gt; best;
    int ans = 0;

    for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++){
        long long x = arr[i];
        vector&lt;long long&gt; divs = getDivisors(x);
        int curMax = 0;
        for (long long d : divs) {
            if (best.find(d) != best.end()){
                curMax = max(curMax, best[d]);
            }
        }
        int dp = curMax + 1;
        best[x] = max(best[x], dp);
        ans = max(ans, dp);
    }
    cout &lt;&lt; ans;
    return 0;
}
